   406→                           Conjectured by Erdős and Simonovits <a href="#cite-ErSi84-147" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErSi84','147'); return false;">[ErSi84]</a>. A probabilistic argument shows that there exists some $\epsilon=\epsilon(H)&gt;0$ such that\[\mathrm{ex}(n;H) \gg n^{2-\frac{2}{r}+\epsilon}.\]This conjecture was disproved by Janzer <a href="#cite-Ja23-147" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Ja23','147'); return false;">[Ja23]</a> for even $r\geq 4$. The case $r=3$ was disproved by Janzer <a href="#cite-Ja23b-147" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Ja23b','147'); return false;">[Ja23b]</a>, who constructed, for any $\epsilon&gt;0$, a $3$-regular bipartite graph $H$ such that\[\mathrm{ex}(n;H)\ll n^{\frac{4}{3}+\epsilon}.\]In <a href="#cite-Ja23-147" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Ja23','147'); return false;">[Ja23]</a> Janzer conjectures that the above lower bound is sharp, in that for any $r\geq 3$ and $\epsilon&gt;0$ there exists an $r$-regular graph $H$ such that\[\mathrm{ex}(n;H) \ll n^{2-\frac{2}{r}+\epsilon}.\]Janzer's result proves this for even $r\geq 4$.<br><br>See also <a href="/113" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[113]</a>, <a href="/146" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[146]</a>, and <a href="/714" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[714]</a>.<br><br>This problem is <a href="https://mathweb.ucsd.edu/~erdosproblems/erdos/newproblems/TuranNondegenerate.html" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">#44 in Extremal Graph Theory</a> in the graphs problem collection.
